  "texts": [
    "We built a VAE model to compute low-dimensional latent variables z ðiÞ 2 R d from high-dimensional omics data fx ðiÞ g i¼1;;N; x ðiÞ 2 R p (N is the number of patients; p is the number of input features [e.g., number of genes]; d is the number of latent variables computed from the input data, and p) d), which can reduce the risk of overfitting in the prognosis prediction task.",
    "Unlike classic autoencoder (AE) models, VAE learns a distribution estimate instead of a point estimate for the low-dimensional latent variables z 54, which can potentially increase the efficiency of the information extraction process and generate \"disentangled\" latent representations of the input features.",
    "This \"disentanglement\" allows qualitatively different information to be encoded into distinct latent variables, which could contribute to a more interpretable VAE model 55, 56.",
    "As illustrated in Fig. 1c, the encoder part of KL-PMVAE consists of a gene layer (each node represents a gene), a pathway layer (each node represents a pathway), and a miRNA layer (each node represents a miRNA).",
    "Reactome 57 pathway information was obtained from the online resource Database for Annotation, Visualization, and Integrated Discovery (DAVID) 58 (by the time we collected the pathway information, DAVID adopted Reactome Fig. 8 Illustration for DeepSHAP implementations."
  ]
